#: Game.Levels.KnightsAndKnaves2
msgid "Say we have an islander §0 who could be a knight or a knave.\n"
"\n"
"§1 is represented as\n"
"§2\n"
"where having the proposition §3 being true means the islander §4 is a knight and having the proposition §5 being false means the islander §6 is a knave.\n"
"\n"
"Now, we intrepret having a proof of §7 as §8 being a knight, and having a proof of §9 as §10 being a knave.\n"
"\n"
"From this, every islander being a knight or a knave is represented as follows:\n"
"§11\n"
"\n"
"Knights always tell the truth, so if §12 makes some statement §13 we have that §14 being a knight implies that the statement §15 is true\n"
"§16\n"
"Moreover, the statement §17 being true means that §18 is telling the truth, i.e. is a knight\n"
"§19\n"
"which can be combined as\n"
"§20\n"
"\n"
"Similarly for §21 being a knave which implies that the statement §22 is false\n"
"§23\n"
"Moreover, the statement §24 being false means that §25 is lying, i.e. is a knave\n"
"§26\n"
"which are combined as\n"
"§27\n"
"\n"
"No islander can be a knight and a knave at the same time because\n"
"§28\n"
"is false.\n"
"\n"
"This representation captures the rules of the knights and knaves puzzle which are:\n"
"- Every islander is either a knight or a knave\n"
"- No islander is both a knight and a knave at the same time\n"
"- Knights always tell the truth, knaves always lie.\n"
"\n"
"Note that you could also take a more explicit truth table approach, where you list all the cases in a truth table and eliminate the cases which contradict the rules of the game (e.g §29 being a knight but §30's statement being false). If you are left with one possibility then the puzzle has a unique solution, otherwise it has multiple solutions.\n"
"This can be done in [prolog](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oEAa2pQKqQU) and [other provers](https://summerofgodel.blogspot.com/2019/04/part-6-propositional-logic-approach-to.html)"
msgstr ""

