#. (stA : A said P)
#. (AKnight : A.isKnight) : P
#. ```
#. §8: ```
#. -- `said_knight`
#. -- If what is said is true,
#. -- then knight.
#. -- A said something true,
#. -- so A is a knight.
#. said_knight
#. (stA : A said P)
#. (hP : P) : A.isKnight
#. ```
#. §9: ```
#. -- `knave_said`
#. -- Whatever a knave says,
#. -- it is false.
#. -- A is a knave,
#. -- so whatever A said is false
#. knave_said
#. (stA : A said P)
#. (AKnave : A.isKnave) : ¬P
#. ```
#. §10: ```
#. -- `said_knave`
#. -- If what is said is false,
#. -- then knave.
#. -- A said something that is false
#. -- (a lie),
#. -- so A is a knave
#. said_knave
#. (stA : A said P)
#. (hnP : ¬P) : A.isKnave
#. ```
#. §11: ```
#. not_isKnight_and_isKnave
#. (A : Islander)
#.   : ¬ (A.isKnight ∧ A.isKnave)
#. ```
#: Game.Levels.DSL_Knights_Knaves
msgid "We will introduce the knights and knaves puzzle here explaining rules of the game and the corresponding §0 representation.\n"
"\n"
"The setting is an island.\n"
"Every islander will make a statement. There are two types of islanders, 'knights' and 'knaves'.\n"
"\n"
"For a given islander §1,\n"
"- The proposition that §2 is a knight:\n"
"§3\n"
"- The proposition that §4 is a knave:\n"
"§5\n"
"\n"
"Every islander is either a knight or a knave:\n"
"§6\n"
"\n"
"Knights always tell the truth, and knaves always lie.\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"§7\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"§8\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"§9\n"
"\n"
"§10\n"
"\n"
"Since knights always tell the truth and knaves always lie, no islander can be both a knight and a knave.\n"
"§11\n"
"\n"
"The objective is to conclude who is a knight and who is a knave, based on the statements of several islanders. This will be done using logical reasoning."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `↔`
#. §1: $
#. \\begin{array}{|c c|c c|c|}
#. \\hline
#. P & Q & P → Q & Q → P & P → Q ∧ Q → P \\\\
#. \\hline
#. T & T & T & T & T \\\\
#. \\hline
#. T & F & F & T & F \\\\
#. \\hline
#. F & T & T & F & F \\\\
#. \\hline
#. F & F & T & T & T \\\\
#. \\hline
#. \\end{array}
#. $
#. §2: `P ↔ Q`
#. §3: `P,Q`
#. §4: `P,Q`
#. §5: `P`
#. §6: `Q`
#. §7: `P`
#. §8: `Q`
#. §9: `PsameQ`
#. §10: `P`
#. §11: `Q`
#. §12: `PsameQ : P ↔ Q`
#. §13: `PsameQ : P = Q`
#. §14: `rw [PsameQ] at hP`
#: Game.Levels.Logic.L07_LogicalEquivalence
msgid "§0 truth table:\n"
"§1\n"
"\n"
"So, §2 is true when §3 are true or §4 are false, i.e. when §5 and §6 have the same\n"
"truth value. Therefore, §7 and §8 are equivalent from a truth value perspective.\n"
"\n"
"Since §9 means that §10 and §11 have the same truth value, you can consider think of §12 as §13 and §14. Try it!"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `knight_to_knave`
#: Game.Levels.DSL_Knights_Knaves.L05_prob29
#: Game.Levels.SetTheory_Knights_Knaves.L05_prob29
msgid "\n"
"Transform the goal from §0.\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `«{hA}»`
#. §1: `«{hB}»`
#. §2: `h`
#. §3: `constructor`
#. §4: `A`
#. §5: `B ∧ C`
#. §6: `⟨⟩`
#. §7: `And.intro`
#. §8: `have`
#. §9: `B ∧ C`
#. §10: `And.intro`
#. §11: `h : B`
#. §12: `stB`
#: Game.Levels.KnightsAndKnaves2.L05_iff
msgid "\n"
"Prove the goal using §0, §1 ,§2.\n"
"\n"
"You can do this in a number of ways:\n"
"\n"
"- Use §3 tactic to split the goal in two, the first being §4 and the second being §5\n"
"- Use §6 notation\n"
"- Use §7\n"
"- Use §8 to first construct a proof of §9 then use §10\n"
"- etc...\n"
"\n"
"The proof of the second case for §11 would require using §12.\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `P ↔ Q`
#. §1: `P`
#. §2: `Q`
#. §3: `P ↔ Q`
#. §4: `P ↔ Q`
#. §5: `P`
#. §6: `Q`
#. §7: ```
#. iff_of_false (ha : ¬a) (hb : ¬b)
#.   : a ↔ b
#. ```
#: Game.Levels.Simp_World.L06_iff_of_false
msgid "§0 means that §1,§2 have the same truth value.\n"
"\n"
"If both of them are true, we can conclude §3.\n"
"\n"
"If both of them are false, we can conclude §4 as well.\n"
"\n"
"Here, we have that §5,§6 are both false.\n"
"\n"
"The relevant theorem,\n"
"§7"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `A`
#. §1: `«{AKnave}».left : A.isKnave`
#: Game.Levels.DSL_Knights_Knaves.L06_prob33
#: Game.Levels.SetTheory_Knights_Knaves.L06_prob33
msgid "\n"
"Now you have that §0 is a knave, which is a contradiction\n"
"\n"
"Remeber that §1.\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `and`
#. §1: `P and Q`
#. §2: `P`
#. §3: `Q`
#. §4: `∧`
#. §5: `∧`
#. §6: `And.intro`
#. §7: `P`
#. §8: `Q`
#. §9: `P ∧ Q`
#. §10: `P`
#. §11: `Q`
#. §12: `T`
#. §13: `F`
#. §14: $$
#. \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|}
#. \\hline
#. x=2 & y=6 & x=2 ∧ y=6 \\\\
#. \\hline
#. T & T & T \\\\
#. \\hline
#. T & F & F \\\\
#. \\hline
#. F & T & F \\\\
#. \\hline
#. F & F & F \\\\
#. \\hline
#. \\end{array}
#. $$
#. §15: `constructor`
#. §16: `P and Q`
#. §17: `P`
#. §18: `Q`
#. §19: `And.intro hP hQ`
#. §20: `\\<hP,hQ\\>`
#: Game.Levels.Logic.L02_And
msgid "Logical connectives are either defined by their introduction and elimination rules or by truth\n"
"tables.\n"
"\n"
"An introduction rule 'introduces' a symbol , in this case proving a statement of §0.\n"
"\n"
"An elimination rule 'eliminates' a symbol extracting information from it. For an expression §1\n"
", applying the elimination rule would give you a proof of §2 and a proof of §3 separately.(seen in future levels)\n"
"\n"
"The only way to introduce the symbol §4 i.e prove a statement involving §5 is to use the\n"
"§6 introduction rule which requires a proof of §7 and a proof of §8.\n"
"\n"
"We can conclude from this that §9 is true in only one case: when §10 is true and §11 is true. It is false otherwise\n"
"\n"
"In truth table form, this looks like:\n"
"\n"
"§12 stands for true\n"
"§13 stands for false\n"
"\n"
"§14\n"
"\n"
"Restart the level and use these two alternative techniques to solve it:\n"
"- You can also use the §15 tactic which will split the goal §16 into two, the first being to prove §17 and the second being to prove §18.\n"
"- Moreover, instead of §19 you can use the notation §20 which means the same thing."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `intro`
#. §1: `P → Q`
#. §2: ```
#. Goal:
#. P → Q
#. ```
#. §3: `P`
#. §4: `Q`
#. §5: `P`
#. §6: `Q`
#. §7: `P`
#. §8: `intro name`
#: Game.Doc.tactic_doc
msgid "§0 tactic is used to deal with goals of the form §1.\n"
"\n"
"Having the following:\n"
"§2\n"
"We want to prove that 'If §3 is true, then §4 is true'.\n"
"\n"
"To do this, we first need to assume §5 then prove §6. Assuming §7 is done using §8 for any 'name'."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `Zoey`
#. §1: `stZ`
#. §2: `constructor`
#. §3: `⟨⟩`
#. §4: `And.intro`
#: Game.Levels.KnightsAndKnaves2.L01_Intro
msgid "\n"
"Prove the second goal using §0, §1\n"
"\n"
"Then close the goal (using §2, or §3 notation, or §4 etc..).\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `False`
#: Game.Doc.doc
msgid "A : I am a knave\n"
"\n"
"This implies a contradiction, §0"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `¬True`
#. §1: `stA`
#. §2: `False`
#. §3: `not_true`
#: Game.Levels.KnightsAndKnaves2.L08_imp
#: Game.Levels.KnightsAndKnaves2.L08_imp
msgid "\n"
"Rewrite §0 in §1 as §2 using §3\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `A`
#. §1: `A`
#. §2: `knave_interp at stA`
#: Game.Levels.SetTheory_Knights_Knaves.L06_prob33
msgid "\n"
"Now that we know that §0 is not a knight, we know that what §1 said was a lie.\n"
"\n"
"§2\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `B`
#: Game.Levels.DSL_Knights_Knaves.L11_prob32
msgid "\n"
"Knowing that §0 is a knight, conclude that there is exactly one knave.\n"
""
msgstr ""

#: Game.Levels.Logic.L08_Not
msgid "Not Connective, ¬"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `A`
#. §1: `A`
#. §2: `«{st}»`
#. §3: `A.isKnave`
#. §4: `knight_to_knave`
#. §5: `«{st}»`
#. §6: `B.isKnave`
#: Game.Levels.DSL_Knights_Knaves.L06_prob33
msgid "\n"
"§0 is not a knight means that §1 is a knave, so §2 could be simplified.\n"
"\n"
"Obtain §3 using §4, and simplify §5 obtaining §6.\n"
"\n"
"After that, close the goal\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `AiffC : A ↔ C`
#. §1: `iff_of_true (ha : a) (hb : b) : a ↔ b`
#. §2: `hA : A`
#. §3: `h : C`
#. §4: `iff_of_true`
#. §5: `P ↔ Q`
#. §6: `P`
#. §7: `Q`
#: Game.Levels.KnightsAndKnaves2.L05_iff
msgid "\n"
"Prove §0 using §1, §2, §3\n"
"\n"
"§4 says that we can conclude §5 is true when §6 is true, §7 is true (check the truth table).\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `P`
#. §1: `¬P`
#. §2: `¬P → False`
#. §3: `¬¬P`
#. §4: `¬¬P`
#. §5: `P`
#. §6: $
#. \\begin{array}{|c | c|c|}
#. \\hline
#. P & ¬P & \\text{¬¬P}\\\\
#. \\hline
#. T & F & T \\\\
#. \\hline
#. F & T & F \\\\
#. \\hline
#. \\end{array}
#. $
#. §7: `¬¬P`
#. §8: `P`
#. §9: ```
#. not_not : ¬¬a ↔ a
#. ```
#. §10: `by_contra`
#. §11: `by_contra h`
#. §12: `h : ¬P`
#: Game.Levels.Simp_World.L05_not_not
msgid "In this level, you will learn 'proof by contradiction'.\n"
"\n"
"To prove §0, you would assume §1 and then prove false, i.e. you would be proving §2 which is §3.\n"
"\n"
"The truth table shows that §4 is equivalent to §5,\n"
"§6\n"
"\n"
"There are two ways to solve this level, and you should try both.\n"
"\n"
"The first way is using the simplification theorem (to simplify §7 to §8),\n"
"§9\n"
"\n"
"The second is using the §10 tactic where §11 would be assuming §12."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `¬isKnight B`
#. §1: `knave_to_knight`
#: Game.Levels.DSL_Knights_Knaves.L03_prob26
msgid "\n"
"Change the goal to §0\n"
"\n"
"Use the §1 tactic.\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `¬P`
#. §1: `¬Q`
#. §2: `P`
#. §3: `Q`
#. §4: ```
#. not_iff_not : (¬a ↔ ¬b) ↔ (a ↔ b)
#. ```
#: Game.Levels.Simp_World.L09_not_iff_not
msgid "If we know that §0,§1 have the same truth value then §2,§3 have the same truth value.\n"
"\n"
"The relevant theorem,\n"
"§4"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `A`
#. §1: `B`
#. §2: `B`
#. §3: `¬(A.isKnight ↔ B.isKnight)`
#. §4: `B`
#. §5: `A.isKnight ↔ B.isKnight`
#. §6: `iff_of_true`
#: Game.Levels.DSL_Knights_Knaves.L07_difftype
msgid "\n"
"So §0,§1 are the same type, but §2 being a knight also tells us that they are not. contradiction\n"
"\n"
"Conclude §3 from §4'statement then prove that §5 using §6\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `Robert`
#. §1: `Ira`
#. §2: `Ira`
#. §3: `Robert`
#. §4: `Ira`
#. §5: ```
#. ( (Ira and Robert)
#. or (¬Ira and ¬Robert)
#. )
#. ```
#. §6: `Ira ↔ Robert`
#. §7: `stR`
#. §8: `Ira ↔ Robert`
#. §9: ```
#. iff_iff_and_or_not_and_not.symm
#. : (a and b or ¬a and ¬b ) ↔ (a ↔ b)
#. ```
#. §10: `stI`
#. §11: `Robert`
#. §12: `Ira`
#: Game.Levels.KnightsAndKnaves2.L03_iff_iff
msgid "§0 says: §1 is my type.\n"
"\n"
"§2 says: §3 is truthful.\n"
"\n"
"'§4 is my type' is translated as\n"
"§5\n"
"Notice that this is equivalent to §6\n"
"\n"
"Replace this expression in §7 by §8 using\n"
"§9\n"
"\n"
"then use §10 to prove §11 and obtain §12."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `∧`
#. §1: `x = 2`
#. §2: `y = 6`
#. §3: ```
#. h : x = 2
#. h' : y = 6
#. ```
#. §4: `x = 2 AND y = 6`
#. §5: `x = 2 ∧ y = 6`
#. §6: `And.intro`
#. §7: `∧`
#. §8: ```
#. And.intro (hP : P)
#.           (hQ : Q)
#. : P and Q
#. ```
#. §9: `And.intro`
#. §10: `P`
#. §11: `Q`
#. §12: `P and Q`
#: Game.Levels.Logic.L02_And
msgid "In this level, we introduce the §0 logical connective (read as 'and').\n"
"\n"
"Given the following proofs that §1 and §2,\n"
"§3\n"
"we can construct a proof that §4 written in Lean notation as §5.\n"
"\n"
"We construct such an expression using an introduction rule called §6 which introduces the §7 symbol\n"
"§8\n"
"\n"
"You can think of §9 as a function that takes two inputs: a proof of §10, a proof of §11 and returns a proof of §12."
msgstr ""

#. §0: `And.intro`
#. §1: `P`
#. §2: `Q`
#. §3: `P ∧ Q`
#. §4: `P Q : Prop`
#. §5: ```
#. hP : P
#. hQ : Q
#. ```
#. §6: `And.intro hP hQ : P ∧ Q`
#. §7: `\\<hP,hQ\\>`
#. §8: ```
#. ⟨hP,hQ⟩ : P ∧ Q
#. ```
#. §9: ```
#. And.intro hP hQ : P ∧ Q
#. ```
#: Game.Doc.doc
msgid "The theorem §0 takes a proof of §1, a proof of §2, and gives a proof of §3 where §4.\n"
"\n"
"Given,\n"
"§5\n"
"we have §6\n"
"\n"
"## Alternative Notation\n"
"Typed as §7,\n"
"§8\n"
"instead of\n"
"§9"
msgstr ""

#. §0: `A`
#. §1: `A`
#: Game.Levels.DSL_Knights_Knaves.L04_IKnaveOrKnave
#: Game.Levels.SetTheory_Knights_Knaves.L04_IKnaveOrKnave
msgid "\n"
"§0's statement is true, so §1 is a knight.\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `A ↔ True`
#. §1: `A`
#. §2: `iff_true_right  (ha : a) : (b ↔ a) ↔ b`
#. §3: `a`
#. §4: `True`
#. §5: `True`
#. §6: `True.intro`
#: Game.Levels.KnightsAndKnaves2.L08_imp
msgid "\n"
"Rewrite §0 to §1 using §2.\n"
"\n"
"Notice that §3 here is §4 and a proof of §5 is simply §6\n"
""
msgstr ""

#. §0: `knight_to_knave`
#: Game.Levels.DSL_Knights_Knaves.L12_31
msgid "\n"
"Convert from §0.\n"
""
msgstr ""
